scope.summary:
GOAL: Create the native Rust GUI crate for Handshake at src/frontend/handshake_native/. This crate is the long-term home of all native GUI code. It must open a real OS window using the toolkit selected in MT-001 (expected: egui + eframe + wgpu), run a render loop, display a minimal shell UI (title bar label + status label), and prove connectivity to the existing handshake_core backend by hitting the GET /health endpoint at 127.0.0.1:37501 and displaying the response status on screen. There is no webview, no Tauri, and no Electron. This MT locks the crate layout and entrypoint binary name that all later MTs extend.

EXPECTED DIFF SHAPE:
  NEW files:
    src/frontend/handshake_native/Cargo.toml
    src/frontend/handshake_native/src/main.rs           (binary entrypoint, calls eframe::run_native)
    src/frontend/handshake_native/src/app.rs            (HandshakeApp struct implementing eframe::App)
    src/frontend/handshake_native/src/backend_client.rs (reqwest-based HTTP client, GET /health)
    src/frontend/handshake_native/src/error.rs          (AppError enum)
    tests/native_gui/test_skeleton.rs                   (kittest smoke test)
  MODIFIED files:
    Cargo.toml  (add src/frontend/handshake_native to [workspace] members)

EXACT CRATE LAYOUT:
  Package name: handshake-native
  Binary name: handshake-native  (produces handshake-native.exe on Windows)
  Edition: 2021
  No lib target — binary only at this stage.
  Crate-type: bin.

DEPENDENCIES to add in src/frontend/handshake_native/Cargo.toml (pin exact versions to match MT-001 spike verdict; if spike chose egui 0.31 / eframe 0.31 / egui_tiles 0.10, use those exact versions):
  eframe = { version = "0.31", default-features = false, features = ["wgpu", "accesskit", "persistence"] }
  egui = "0.31"
  egui_tiles = { version = "0.10", features = ["serde"] }
  accesskit = "0.17"
  accesskit_winit = "0.22"
  reqwest = { version = "0.12", default-features = false, features = ["json", "rustls-tls"] }
  tokio = { version = "1", features = ["rt", "rt-multi-thread", "macros"] }
  serde = { version = "1", features = ["derive"] }
  serde_json = "1"
  tracing = "0.1"
  tracing-subscriber = { version = "0.3", features = ["env-filter"] }

REACT REFERENCE — App.tsx layout to understand the shell structure being replaced:
  The React app (app/src/App.tsx lines 1-120) defines the top-level shell: a workspace sidebar on the left, a main pane area in the center, and a status bar. The WorkspaceSidebar component (app/src/components/WorkspaceSidebar.tsx) is the left panel. This MT does NOT port the sidebar yet — it only creates an empty shell window with title + status label as placeholders.

BACKEND API BOUND:
  GET http://127.0.0.1:37501/health
  Response type (from handshake_core::models::HealthResponse):
    { "status": "ok" | "error", "db_status": "ok" | "error" | "unknown", "migration_version": <i64 | null> }
  The backend listens on 127.0.0.1:37501 (hardcoded in handshake_core/src/main.rs line 41).
  The native app must NOT start the backend — it assumes the backend is already running. If /health returns a non-200 or errors, display an error label in the status bar.

HANDSHAKEAPP STRUCT (src/frontend/handshake_native/src/app.rs):
  pub struct HandshakeApp {
    health_status: HealthDisplayState,
    health_poll_handle: Option<tokio::task::JoinHandle<HealthResponse>>,
    rt: tokio::runtime::Runtime,   // single tokio runtime owned by the app
  }
  enum HealthDisplayState { Loading, Ok { migration_version: Option<i64> }, Error(String) }
  impl eframe::App for HandshakeApp {
    fn update(&mut self, ctx: &egui::Context, _frame: &mut eframe::Frame) {
      // 1. Poll the health_poll_handle if Some; on completion set health_status.
      // 2. Render top panel with label "Handshake" (AccessKit author_id: NodeId(1)).
      // 3. Render bottom panel with health status string (author_id: NodeId(2)).
      // 4. Request repaint if still Loading.
    }
  }
  impl HandshakeApp {
    pub fn new(cc: &eframe::CreationContext) -> Self { ... }
  }

ACCESSKIT REQUIREMENTS:
  Every widget rendered in this MT must have a stable AccessKit author_id and role:
    - Title label "Handshake": NodeId(1), Role::Label
    - Health status label: NodeId(2), Role::Label
    - Main content area frame: NodeId(3), Role::Region
  Set author IDs using egui widget .id(egui::Id::new("handshake_title")) and ensure accesskit_winit adapter is initialised in the eframe creation context so the AccessKit tree is live from the first frame.

ENTRYPOINT (src/frontend/handshake_native/src/main.rs):
  fn main() -> eframe::Result<()> {
    tracing_subscriber::fmt().with_env_filter("handshake_native=debug,eframe=info").init();
    let native_options = eframe::NativeOptions {
      viewport: egui::ViewportBuilder::default()
        .with_title("Handshake")
        .with_inner_size([1280.0, 800.0])
        .with_min_inner_size([640.0, 480.0]),
      renderer: eframe::Renderer::Wgpu,
      ..Default::default()
    };
    eframe::run_native(
      "handshake-native",
      native_options,
      Box::new(|cc| Ok(Box::new(HandshakeApp::new(cc)))),
    )
  }

TEST (tests/native_gui/test_skeleton.rs):
  Use egui_kittest::Harness to run HandshakeApp headlessly for 2 frames. Assert that the egui Id for 'handshake_title' exists in the widget tree. Assert the window title is 'Handshake'. This test must NOT require a live backend — mock the health response by injecting a pre-set HealthDisplayState::Ok into HandshakeApp before the harness runs.

FONT: Load Inter from the bundled assets path (to be defined in MT-004). For MT-002, fall back to eframe default font (no custom font loading yet — that is MT-003's dependency).
